title: Planting Positivity
description:
Planting Positivity is a series of 38 podcasts to help you, to help yourself!
You wont get it all done, so stop trying!
You won't get permission, so stop asking!
Instead be more like a flower, it doesn't need permission, it doesn't have to be super busy all the time, it doesn't need justification, clarification, or credibility it just is! It grows, it blooms, its beautiful, it just is!
Happiness and Positivity are a mindset, when  planted, watered and nurtured,  they grow, when weeded and pruned, they flourish, enabling you to bloom in life. To thrive rather than survive. 
Don't be like the salmon thrashing about upstream, relax, let go and go with the flow. 
It is not all about 6 figure incomes, sweating and stressing through life, proving you're a superwoman because look you can juggle baby, take the kids to numerous weekly activities (that they probably don't even want to do, by the way) be busy and super efficient at work, cook like Delia Smith and bake like Mary Berry and still have energy to be a loving wife, FFS*! its about enjoying the here and now. Its about aligning and finding the peace within, to be able to find your authentic voice and use it to get what you want. Its learning to say "NO! I'm not going to do that, because it is not in line with my happiness"  Your happiness, your joy, your  inner peace  are too important to keep at the back door, too important to brush aside and hope you'll find time for them later. 
Explore who you are, learn about you and how your mind works and learn how to embrace the wonderfulness of you, so you can get purposeful on getting more positive.

title: Exploring Ethical Considerations of Technology in the Classroom
description:
Exploring Ethical Considerations of Technology in the Classroom

Welcome to Exploring Ethical Considerations of Technology in the Classroom, the podcast where we discuss the critical issues influencing education today. In this episode, we'll talk over the ethical concerns and duties that come with using technology in the classroom. We'll look at the complications of incorporating technology while maintaining a safe and fair learning environment, from student privacy to digital citizenship.

Our journey begins with one important consideration: student privacy. Students' personal and sensitive data are more at risk as technology is integrated into schooling. Data breaches have prompted worries about how schools and educational technology businesses protect this information. It is not only about learning.

However, ethical considerations go beyond facts. The digital world introduces new problems to kid safety and well-being. The impact on students' mental and emotional health cannot be overstated as they spend more time online. Educators are now in charge of creating a safe digital environment and teaching kids appropriate digital habits.

Speaking of habits, let's move on to digital citizenship. Understanding ethical online behaviour is critical in an age of constant connectivity. Educators must help kids navigate the digital realm responsibly, from proper netiquette to addressing the negative aspects of online interactions like cyber bullying and misinformation.

Now, let's talk about a problem that extends beyond behaviour and impacts on social equality. Although technology provides limitless educational materials, what if not every student has equal access? The digital divide raises ethical concerns regarding how to provide equitable opportunities for all students, regardless of background.

One thing becomes evident as we traverse these difficult ethical considerations: the need for partnership. Parents, guardians, communities, and policymakers must all be included in the discussion. In order to resolve issues, promote responsible technology use, and develop ethical principles for technology integration, inclusivity and transparent communication are required.

Addressing ethical issues in technology helps me as an educator to establish a responsible and ethical digital learning environment. It enables them to assist students in safely and ethically navigating the digital realm.

exploring these consequences with students empowers them to be thoughtful and informed digital citizens. It gives students the tools they need to interact with technology in ways that improve their learning, personal development, and future interactions in the digital world.

Finally, knowing and debating the ethical issues of technology use in education benefits both educators and students' digital literacy. It enables instructors to successfully guide students and trains them to engage with technology responsibly, building a healthy and ethical digital society.
